  "response": "In the United States, these topics are typically covered in the following grades/levels:\n\n1. Derivatives and Integrals: \n- Usually introduced in 11th or 12th grade (Advanced Placement Calculus)\n- More deeply studied in first-year college calculus courses\n\n2. Organic Chemistry:\n- Typically learned in high school Advanced Placement (AP) Chemistry (11th or 12th grade)\n- More comprehensively studied in college-level chemistry courses\n\n3. Waves:\n- Basic wave concepts are introduced in middle school (around 7th-8th grade)\n- More detailed wave physics and mathematics are covered in high school physics (10th-12th grade)\n- Advanced wave theory is studied in college-level physics courses\n\nThe exact timing can vary depending on the school, curriculum, and whether a student is taking advanced or standard-level courses. Advanced or honors students might encounter these topics earlier or in more depth.",
